Chem 10.1002/ajoc.202000484 Link to VoR: https://doi.org/10.1002/ajoc.202000484 In this minireview, we have highlighted various developments related to the total synthesis of  anticancer  agent,  fredericamycin  A  (NSC-305263).  The  presence  of  a  unique  molecular  architecture  and  significant  biological  properties  associated  with  fredericamycin  A,  have  greatly enhanced the research activity and we cover total synthesis of this molecule since its  isolation.  Different methodologies adopted for the construction of stereogenic spiro centre are  radical spirocyclization, Diels ̶Alder (DA) reaction, [3+2] annulation, photochemical approach,  ring-closing  metathesis  (RCM),  palladium-catalyzed  cross-coupling  reaction,  rearrangement  approach,  benzannulation  etc.  This  minireview  will  provide  an  overview  of  contribution  of  different  research  groups  in  the  total  synthesis  of  fredericamycin  A.  We  also  cover  various  model studies related to the synthesis of this molecule.   Department of Chemistry, Indian Institute of Technology-Bombay, Powai, Mumbai-400076, India  Synthetic Approaches to the Anticancer Agent Fredericamycin A

Fax: 022-25767152; E-mail: srk@chem.iitb.ac.in  Sambasivarao Kotha* and Ambareen Fatma  Fredericamycin  A  (1)  (FM-A  NSC-305263)  is  an  antitumor  antibiotic  isolated  from  the  fermentation broth of soil bacterium Streptomyces griseus (FCRC- 48) at Frederick Maryland  in 1981. [1a] It is a hexacyclic quinone based natural product with a novel spiro [4.4] nonane  ring,  not  observed  previously  in  any  antibiotic  connected  with  naphtoquinoline  and  isoquinoline  aromatic  moieties.  The  structure  of  this  highly  oxygenated  compound  was  established  by  single  crystal  X-ray  diffraction  studies,[1b]  further  confirmed  by  both  spectroscopic and mass spectrometric data.[1b, 1c] The quaternary spiro ring is chiral due to the  presence of single methoxy group at the distant A ring of the molecule, while the configuration  of  single  chiral  centre  was  later  assigned  to  be  S  configuration  by  Kita’s  group  in  2001.[2a]  Fredericamycin A is a biologically active compound and exhibits antibacterial, antifungal and  cytotoxic activity. It shows cytotoxic activity against murine leukemia KB, Du-145 prostrate  tumors, P338D1 mouse leukemia, CD8F mammary cell lines etc.[2b] Compound 1 is also known  to inhibit DNA processing enzymes such as topoisomerase I and  II.[3] In view of its unique  molecular architecture and significant biological activity various research groups directed their  efforts towards the total synthesis of fredericamycin A.[4] To the best of our knowledge till date  a review on synthesis of fredericamycin A has not appeared. Therefore, here we provide the  literature  survey  dealing  with  its  total  synthesis,  both  asymmetric  and  racemic  forms.  Six

research groups Kelly,[4b, 4c] Clive,[5a] Rama Rao,[5b] Kita,[5c] Bach,[5d] and Julia [10f] reported the  total synthesis of racemic form of fredericamycin A.  Later on, assymetric total synthesis and  total synthesis of optically pure form of 1 has also been disclosed.[4f, 6] The presence of unusual  spiro  ring  has  led  to  the  exploration  of  several  synthetic  routes.  Numerous  examples  are  available dealing with the model studies for constructing the synthetically challenging spiro  system of this molecule.[7] The compounds in Figure 2 shows close structural resemblance to  fredericamycin A.[1g-1i]  Figure 1. Structure of fredericamycin A 1  To provide complete literature survey for all the model studies are beyond the scope of this  review,  although  we  are  compiling  major  synthetic  approaches  leading  to  functionalized  fragments (partial structure) of 1. This minireview focusses on both model studies as well as  total synthesis of fredericamycin A 1. In this minireview we covered various approaches in a  Figure 2. Isolation and Biological Significance of Fredericamycin A  Fredericamycin A (FCRC-48) was isolated by Pandey et.al in 1981, and its fermentation strain  was identified as Streptomyces griseus ATCC49344.[1b] It is a bioactive compound and shows  in  vitro activity against  Gram-positive bacteria  and  in  vivo activity  against  P388 tumor cell  lines.[2b] The best purification method for fredericamycin A was preparative TLC using solvent  system  such  as  CHCl3-MeOH-AcOH  (87:3:3),  fredericamycin B and C (brownish red solid) were also isolated as minor components. Since  these  minor  components  did  not  show  any  bioactivity  and  hence  further  studies  are  not  available. The structure of fredericamycin A was established in 1982 by single crystal XRD

studies which was further supported by mass and spectroscopic data (mp ˃ 350 ℃).[1b] Several  physiochemical  properties  of  fredericamycin  A  was  proved  by  spectroscopic  method,  for  example, IR spectra shows a band at 1720 cm-1 representating conjugated carbonyl group, two  hydroxyl peaks are hydrogen bonded, high resolution electron impact mass spectrometric data  (HREIMS) shows molecular ion peak at m/z 539.1218.[1c] Molecular mass is further confirmed  thus  along  with  fredericamycin  A,  by  other  mass  spectrometric  methods  such  as  FDMS,  FABMS.  Additionally,  UV-visible  spectra showed the presence of ionizable group in fredericamycin A, isobestic point at 554 nm.  13C  NMR  spectroscopy  showed  14  carbon  signals  and  among  these  12  belongs  to  olefinic  region. Apart from this, 1 also acts as an acid-base indicator, it is sparingly soluble in most of  the polar solvents but completely soluble in DMSO, DMF and acetic acid.[1a] It is interesting  to note that fredericamycin A due to extended conjugation half of its 1H NMR and its 13C NMR  peaks are invisible. This molecule assumes several different tautomers. However, by addition  of trace of trifluoracetic acid shifts the equilibrium to one side, the signals of missing carbon  reappear.[1j] In 1986, Hilton and Misra demonstrated the antitumor and antibacterial activity of  1 is due to the generation of superoxide O2 further examined in 1989 by an ESR experiment. For this purpose, natural fredericamycin A  was dissolved in DMSO and dilute H2O2, which shows neither the formation of O2 radicals or ̇OH free radical.[1e]   3. 3.6 [3+2] Annulation Approach for Spirocyclic Core of Fredericamycin A 1 (Moser and  In 2002, Moser et.al demonstrated the construction of spirocyclic core of fredericamycin A  (Scheme  6)  which  involves  the  generation  of  polycyclic  and  spirocyclic  center  via  [3+2]  annulation  (aldol  reaction/Brook  rearrangement/cylization).[7o]  Their  synthesis  commenced  with the preparation of spiro compound 27 by a three-step synthetic sequence. Decomplexation  of  27  was  achieved  by  exposure  to  air/light  to  afford  28,  deprotection  of  28  followed  by  oxidation furnished the dione 7 in 62% yield.  Scheme 6. [3+2] annulation approach to BCDE unit of 1 (Moser and co-workers).7o  3.7 Claisen rearrangement and Ring-closing Metathesis (RCM) Approach for the ABCD  ring system of Fredericamycin A 1 (Kotha and co-workers)  Recently in 2019, Kotha and co-workers designed the ABCD ring system of fredericamycin A  by  adopting  a  double-Claisen  rearrangement  and  ring-closing  metathesis  (RCM)  as  key  This strategy is somewhat unique since the quaternary spirocyclic centre is created by allylation  and RCM protocol for the first time. The synthetic plan commenced with the RCM of diallyl  compound 31 to furnish the spiro derivative 32 in 89% yield. CAN oxidation of 32 followed  by  DA  reaction  produces  the  adduct  34,  which  was  subsequently  treated  with  SiO2  for  aromatization. [8a, 8d] Next step involves the O-allylation of aromatized compound 35, one-pot  double-Claisen rearrangement and retro- Diels ̶ Alder (rDA)[8f] reaction and RCM to produce

38. These linear synthetic sequences provided the basic ABCD ring skeleton of 1. Finally, SeO2  oxidation  of  38  afforded  the  dione  39  constituting  the  ABCD  fragment  of  1  with  fully  functionalized BC ring system (Scheme 7).    Scheme 7. Various Synthetic Routes by different groups in the Total Synthesis of FredericamycinA  4.1 Total Synthesis of Racemic Fredericamycin A via Intramolecular Aldol Condensation  Kelly and Ohashi communicated the first total synthesis of (±)-fredericamycin A in 1986 as a  yellow  crystalline  substance  confirmed  by  single  crystal  X-ray  analysis  and  later  in  1988  published  the  details  of  their  study.[4a-4c]  Initially  they  demonstrated  model  studies  for  the  preparation of the  key  synthons and resolved the regiochemical problems in  coupling of key  synthons  40  and  42  (Scheme  8).[9] To  begin  with,  the  coupling  partners  isoquinoline  40  and  anhydride 42 were synthesized by modification of literature procedure. The silyl anion 41 and  anhydride 42 were combined by lactonization to provide hexacyclic system 43. It is noteworthy  that substitution of bulky silyl group facilitates the acylation at the desired site.   fredericamycin A 1 (Kotha and co-workers).7i  Scheme 8. Total synthesis of (±)- fredericamycin A 1 by intramolecular aldol condensation  approach (Kelly and co-workers).4c  Next, DIBAL reduction of 43 followed by intramolecular aldol condensation produces the four  diastereomers containing spiro ring which upon Swern oxidation furnished the diketone 46 in  40% yield from 42. Treatment of 46 with Pd/C reduces the double bond in indene ring as well

as  deprotects  the  benzylic  alcohol  to  give  47  which  upon  exposure  to  air  provides  quinone  derivative 48 in 78% overall yield after two steps. The acetal group in 48 was hydrolysed to  the  aldehyde  derivative  49  in  which  pentadienyl  group  was  introduced  in  the  presence  of  Horner reagent to produce a mixture of cis and trans diastereomers 50. In the final step exposure  to  I2  not  only  solved  the  stereochemistry  of  the  double  bond  and  produced  the  thermodynamically  stable  trans,  trans  isomer  and  also  deprotects  MOM/OMe  group  to  complete the total synthesis of 1 in racemic form (Scheme 8).  4.2  Total  synthesis  (±)-  fredericamycin  A  via  radical  spirocyclization  (Clive  and  co- In 1992, Clive and co-workers published the synthesis of (±)-1 by employing radical cyclization  as a key step and disclosed a detail study in 1994.[5a, 4d] In the preceding year, they reported the  model study and solved various problems encountered in their earlier approach towards the total  synthesis  of  fredericamycin  A.[10a]  For  example,  the  problem  of  geometrical  isomers  of  pentadienyl  side  chain  was  solved  in  an  unexpected  manner,  radical  spirocyclization[10b]  proceeded well as compared to ionic reaction for the construction of congested quaternary spiro  ring  system.    Interestingly  improved  synthetic  plan  involves  combining  the  two  subunits  51  (FED)  and  lithiated  benzene  derivatives  (AB  fragment)  52  of  fredericamycin  by  following  a  similar  strategy  reported  in  the  literature.  [10b]  Later,  linking  these  two  subunits  and  spirocyclization produces the key intermediate suitable for fredericamycin. The coupled hydroxy

derivative  53  was  oxidized  efficiently  by  using  triphenylbismuth  carbonate.    Introduction  of  phenylselenyl (PhSe) group for radical process is not an easy task and several methods failed.  Fortunately,  LDA  and  nBuLi  under  optimized  reaction  conditions  gave  55  in  70%  yield.  Realization  of  the  desired  cyclization  led  to  the  spiro  system  56,  which  was  obtained  in  the  presence  of  triphenyltin  hydride  and  triethylborane  under  aerobic  conditions.  Next  exocyclic  double  bond  was  hydroxylated,  cleavage  (5𝟓 →5𝟔 → 𝟓𝟕),  followed  by  the  deprotection  of  hydroxy group and oxidation generate the aldehyde derivate 60. To complete the synthesis, the  next task is attaching pentadienyl side chain to the A ring of the molecule which was realized  efficiently by the Wittig reaction. [5b]   Scheme 11 Total synthesis of (±)-fredericamycin A via Radical cyclization (Rama Rao and co- workers).5b  During  these  investigations  they  also  reported  the  key  synthon  (ABC  fragment,  a  benzphtalide)[11d,  11e]  and  (DEF  fragment,  an  isoquinoline  moeity)[11i]  for  the  total  synthesis.  After  completion  of  model  studies,  in  1993  they  published  the  total  synthesis  of  racemic  fredericamycin  which  involve  the  LDA  mediated  aldol  condensation  of  subunits  67  and  69  followed by rearrangement of aldol product 70 in the presence of sodium methoxide to produce

1,3-dione in 58% yield.[5b] The dione was transformed into chloro/bromo derivatives, however  chloro derivative upon reductive cyclization resulted in low yield of the product (10%). Whereas,  the bromo derivative undergo radical cyclization in the presence of Ph3SnH in benzene at reflux  temperature generate the protected derivative of fredericamycin 75. Finally, deprotection with  BBr3 affords crystalline (±)- fredericamycin in good yield (Scheme 11).   4.4 Total synthesis of (±)-fredericamycin A by aldol-type condensation and 1,4-addition  Julia proposed the total synthesis of racemic form of 1 in 1993 by using Kuwajima reaction as  a key step. His linear approach involves the aldol-type condensation between the acetal 76 and  1,2-bis(trimethylsiloxy)cyclobutene  77.  To  this  end,  Lewis-acid  catalyzed  rearrangement  of  cyclobutene derivative gave the spirodiketone 78, which on treatment with DBU facilitate the  incorporation  of  the  double-bond  in  C  ring  of  compound  79.  Next,  1,4-addition  reaction  between 79 and 80 furnishes the condensation product 81 which on cyclization in the presence  of sodium hydride and sodium methoxide gave the hexacyclic compound 82 in 95% yield. In  the  final  step,  six  methoxy  groups  out  of  seven  was  deprotected  by  BBr3  and  further  air  oxidation delivers (±)- fredericamycin A.[11f]   Scheme 12. Total synthesis of (±)-fredericamycin A (Julia and co-workers).11f  4.5 Pinacol Type Rearrangement and 1,4-Cycloaddiion Approach in the Total Synthesis  of (±)- Fredericamycin A (Bach and co-workers)   The total synthesis of racemic fredericamycin has been reported by Bach and co-workers in  1994.[5d] Their efforts directed towards the formal synthesis of fredericamycin were supported

by several model studies.[12] During the course of their investigation three reports on the total  synthesis of fredericamycin A has been published by other groups.[5a, 5b] Taking the advantage  of their previous studies they constructed the two key synthons 95 and 96.[12c]   Scheme 13. Total synthesis of (±)- fredericamycin A by (Bach and co-workers).5d   The  key  steps  for  their  assembly  are  mercury  mediated  pinacol  type  rearrangement  for  the  construction of spiro ring and 1,3-dipolar cycloaddition reaction. To begin with, spiro system  85  was  synthesized  via  pinacol  type  rearrangement  of  84  in  the  presence  of  mercuric  acetate.[12c]  In  the  next  step  the  dione  85  was  transformed  into  ketal  86  which  was  stereoselectively brominated followed by protection of the phenol to produce 88 in 94% yield.   Next their efforts were directed towards the introduction of carbonyl group and pentadienenyl  chain in the F ring. For this purpose, 88 was subjected to metalation reaction to generate ester  derivative 89. Methyl anion 90 was also generated by using LiTMP which was converted into  cuprate and reacted with sorobyl chloride gave the isochromarin derivative 92 in a modest yield  (68%).  Conversion  of  isochromarin  to  isoquinolone  followed  by  diacetal  deprotection  and  introduction  of  the  double  bond  into  the  C  ring  was  carried  out  by  well-established  procedure.[12d,  12e]  The  two  fragments  95  and  96  on  treatment  with  LDA  induces  Michael  addition which upon treatment with weak base afforded the ring closure product  98 in 78%  yield (overall 2 steps). Finally, demethylation of E ring and air oxidation of A ring completes  the convergent total synthesis of (±)-fredericamycin A (Scheme 13).

4.6 Diels ̶ Alder/Benzannulation/Aldol condensation Approach in the Total Synthesis of  Boger published the total synthesis of natural and enantiomeric fredericamycin in 1995.[6]   Based  on  their  reports  for  the  construction  of  partial  structure  involving  the  regiospecific  intermolecular Dötz benzannulation for AB ring construction, aldol reaction for installation of  spiro CD ring system and DA reaction for F ring construction. [7a]  Scheme 15. Construction of ABCDE fragment of fredericamycin A (Boger and co-workers).7a  Boger and co-workers succeeded in the synthesis of optically pure form of 1 by separation of  racemic 1 through HPLC. Their synthesis begins with the preparation of DEF ring moiety 116  via a six-step sequence (Scheme 16).[13] The keto group in 116 was converted into nitrile under  optimized conditions. This approach involves the introduction of pentadienyl side chain at the  initial stage via a two-step sequence followed by transformation of nitrile 119 to aldehyde 120.  By following their previous approach for installation of AB and CD ring system, the protected  alkyne 122 was synthesized in 54% yield (2 steps) which was treated with chromium carbene  complex  123  in  the  presence  of  heptane/Ac2O  to  produce  the  benzannulated  product  124.  Subsequent protection of the diol and phenol moieties in 124 prevents side reaction. [2a] Further,

deprotection of the diol moiety, oxidation and aldol ring closure in the presence of base like  DBU  generates  the  basic  skeleton  of  fredericamycin.  In  the  final  step  treatment  with  BBr3  promotes deprotection of methoxy group and oxidation in air completes the total synthesis of  natural  fredericamycin. Later,  deacetylation  followed  by  oxidation  furnished  the  tetracyclic  compound  132,  ABCD  ring fragment of fredericamycin.[14]   Scheme  17.  Synthesis  of  partial  structure  of  fredericamycin  A  via  [4+2]  cycloaddition  by  4.7.2 [4+2] Cycloaddition Approach to Asymmetric Total Synthesis of Fredericamycin A  In 1999, Kita’s group reported asymmetric synthesis  [14a] of fredericamycin A by employing  [4+2]  intermolecular  cycloaddition  reaction  between  suitably  functionalized  regioisomeric  homophthalic anhydride (diene) 140 or 141 and the dienophile 139 (Scheme 18) constituting  CDEF ring moiety.[14] The synthetic plan commenced with the asymmetric reduction of 133

using chiral borane followed by Sharpless epoxidation to give cis-epoxy alcohol ( ̶ )- 134 in  (74% ee).[14a] Mitsunobu reaction of 134 in the presence of camphanic acid converts it into a  diastereomeric  mixture  of  chromatography  produces  optically  pure  ( ̶)-134  (≥99%  de).  Next,  BF3.OEt2  mediated  rearrangement at 0 ℃ produces spiro compound 136 in 94 % yield (≥99% ee). Later, 136 was  transformed into 139 via α, α-disulfenylation of (+)-137 followed by removal of PhSH in the  presence of acid. Finally its oxidation produced the spiro compound 139 as a diastereomeric  mixture (1:1).[15b] Regioisomeric dienes 140 and 141 were synthesized based on the reported  procedure.[15c]  With  diene  and  dienophiles  in  hand,  [4+2]  cycloaddition  of  139  with  the  substrates  140  and  141  gave  the  cycloadducts  (R)-142  and  (S)-143  respectively  under  the  similar reaction conditions. Circular dichroism data of both the enantiomers showed that (S)- 143 closely resembles that of protected fredericamycin. Thus (S)-143 isomer was subjected to  trans-epoxy  camphanate  (74%  de).  Silica  gel  column  F-ring deprotection followed by oxidation to produce aldehyde to  install of pentadienyl chain  using  Wittig  reaction  (Scheme  19).[4d,  15d]  However,  Wittig  reaction  produced  a  mixture  of  geometrical  isomers  which  was  then  subjected  to  deprotection  of  OMe  followed  by  autooxidation to produce (E,E)-isomer and (E,Z)-isomer in 74% yield. Later the desired (E,E)  isomer 1 was obtained by HPLC separation.
